<subSubSection lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="7" pageId="7" pageNumber="6" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="7.[193,1442,1601,1914]" lastBlockId="8.[192,1440,194,314]" lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="7" pageId="7" pageNumber="6">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[193,329,1601,1625]" pageId="7" pageNumber="6">Diagnosis</emphasis>
. Smaller adults, length 
<quantity box="[628,761,1602,1626]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.2" metricValueMax="1.3" metricValueMin="1.1" pageId="7" pageNumber="6" unit="mm" value="12.0" valueMax="13.0" valueMin="11.0">11–13 mm</quantity>
. Pattern of elytral vestiture distinctive (
<figureCitation box="[1257,1363,1602,1626]" captionStart="Figures 1–9" captionStartId="5.[192,288,1044,1066]" captionTargetBox="[192,1440,192,1024]" captionTargetId="figure-218@5.[192,1440,192,1024]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figures 1–9. Adult habitus images of specimens of species in the ancora species group, from the TMSA collection. Specimen identifications by P. Basilewsky are given in brackets after the current valid name for the specimen figured. 1) G. ancora Dejean [G. ancora ancora Dejean], Hanover, Northern Cape Province, RSA. 2) G. distinctus Péringuey [G. fasciatus distinctus Péringuey], Shilouvane, Limpopo Province, RSA. 3) G. fasciatus Chaudoir [G. fasciatus fasciatus Chaudoir], Umfolozi, KwaZulu/Natal Province, RSA. 4) G. fritschi Chaudoir, Pietersburg, Limpopo Province, RSA. 5) G. westwoodi Brême [G. ancora aurantiacus Basilewsky], Bulawayo, Zimbabwe. 6) G. westwoodi [G. ancora egressus Péringuey], Ohrigstad, Mpumalanga Province, RSA. 7) G. westwoodi [G. ancora subegregius Basilewsky, paratype], Tuli District, Botswana. 8) G. westwoodi [G. ancora transitans Péringuey], Metsimaklaba, Botswana. 9) G. westwoodi [G. ancora westwoodi Brême], Swartruggens Marico, North West Province, RSA." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5174194" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5174194/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="6">Figure 2</figureCitation>
), with the elytra covered in contrasting black and yellowish-grey pubescence. Basal half of elytron with a black linear band of pubescence along suture and a triangular patch of black pubescence completely surrounded by yellowish-grey pubescence; apical half of elytron predominantly covered in black pubescence but with a small ovate patch of yellowish-grey pubescence along the suture at apex, an angled median band of yellowish-grey pubescence which is contiguous with the patches of yellowish-grey pubescence on the basal half, and a narrow lateral band of yellowish-grey pubescence which connects the apical and median patches of yellowish-grey pubescence. The pronotal vestiture is likewise distinctive in that the median longitudinal band of black pubescence is more or less equal in width from base to apex. The shape of the patches of pubescence will readily separate individuals of this species from those of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Chaudoir" authorityYear="1870" box="[192,337,194,218]" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Graphipterus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="7" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fasciatus">
<emphasis box="[192,337,194,218]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="7">G. fasciatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which has much more extensive areas of black pubescence on the elytra, and in which the median longitudinal band of dark pubescence on the pronotum becomes distinctly wider from base to apex (
<figureCitation box="[266,373,258,282]" captionStart="Figures 1–9" captionStartId="5.[192,288,1044,1066]" captionTargetBox="[192,1440,192,1024]" captionTargetId="figure-218@5.[192,1440,192,1024]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figures 1–9. Adult habitus images of specimens of species in the ancora species group, from the TMSA collection. Specimen identifications by P. Basilewsky are given in brackets after the current valid name for the specimen figured. 1) G. ancora Dejean [G. ancora ancora Dejean], Hanover, Northern Cape Province, RSA. 2) G. distinctus Péringuey [G. fasciatus distinctus Péringuey], Shilouvane, Limpopo Province, RSA. 3) G. fasciatus Chaudoir [G. fasciatus fasciatus Chaudoir], Umfolozi, KwaZulu/Natal Province, RSA. 4) G. fritschi Chaudoir, Pietersburg, Limpopo Province, RSA. 5) G. westwoodi Brême [G. ancora aurantiacus Basilewsky], Bulawayo, Zimbabwe. 6) G. westwoodi [G. ancora egressus Péringuey], Ohrigstad, Mpumalanga Province, RSA. 7) G. westwoodi [G. ancora subegregius Basilewsky, paratype], Tuli District, Botswana. 8) G. westwoodi [G. ancora transitans Péringuey], Metsimaklaba, Botswana. 9) G. westwoodi [G. ancora westwoodi Brême], Swartruggens Marico, North West Province, RSA." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5174194" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5174194/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="7">Figure 2</figureCitation>
). Small adults of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Dejean" authorityYear="1831" box="[588,708,258,281]" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Graphipterus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="7" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ancora">
<emphasis box="[588,708,258,281]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="7">G. ancora</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are also similar but that species is generally larger in body size (length 
<quantity box="[342,471,290,314]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.55" metricValueMax="1.8" metricValueMin="1.3" pageId="8" pageNumber="7" unit="mm" value="15.5" valueMax="18.0" valueMin="13.0">13–18 mm</quantity>
) and the elytral vestiture is coarser and more irregular (
<figureCitation box="[1170,1274,290,314]" captionStart="Figures 1–9" captionStartId="5.[192,288,1044,1066]" captionTargetBox="[192,1440,192,1024]" captionTargetId="figure-218@5.[192,1440,192,1024]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figures 1–9. Adult habitus images of specimens of species in the ancora species group, from the TMSA collection. Specimen identifications by P. Basilewsky are given in brackets after the current valid name for the specimen figured. 1) G. ancora Dejean [G. ancora ancora Dejean], Hanover, Northern Cape Province, RSA. 2) G. distinctus Péringuey [G. fasciatus distinctus Péringuey], Shilouvane, Limpopo Province, RSA. 3) G. fasciatus Chaudoir [G. fasciatus fasciatus Chaudoir], Umfolozi, KwaZulu/Natal Province, RSA. 4) G. fritschi Chaudoir, Pietersburg, Limpopo Province, RSA. 5) G. westwoodi Brême [G. ancora aurantiacus Basilewsky], Bulawayo, Zimbabwe. 6) G. westwoodi [G. ancora egressus Péringuey], Ohrigstad, Mpumalanga Province, RSA. 7) G. westwoodi [G. ancora subegregius Basilewsky, paratype], Tuli District, Botswana. 8) G. westwoodi [G. ancora transitans Péringuey], Metsimaklaba, Botswana. 9) G. westwoodi [G. ancora westwoodi Brême], Swartruggens Marico, North West Province, RSA." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5174194" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5174194/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="7">Figure 1</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="8" pageNumber="7" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="8.[192,1439,353,410]" pageId="8" pageNumber="7">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,372,353,377]" pageId="8" pageNumber="7">Distribution.</emphasis>
<collectingCountry box="[379,540,354,378]" name="Mozambique" pageId="8" pageNumber="7">Mozambique</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[552,855,354,378]" name="South Africa" pageId="8" pageNumber="7">Republic of South Africa</collectingCountry>
(
<collectingRegion box="[871,979,354,378]" country="South Africa" name="Limpopo" pageId="8" pageNumber="7">Limpopo</collectingRegion>
and 
<collectingRegion box="[1042,1206,354,378]" country="South Africa" name="Mpumalanga" pageId="8" pageNumber="7">Mpumalanga</collectingRegion>
Provinces), 
<collectingCountry name="Swaziland" pageId="8" pageNumber="7">Swaziland</collectingCountry>
. For a list of collecting localities see 
<bibRefCitation author="Basilewsky, P." box="[698,970,386,410]" pageId="8" pageNumber="7" pagination="1 - 472" refId="ref7374" refString="Basilewsky, P. 1977. Revision du genre Graphipterus Latreille (Coleoptera Carabidae). Musee Royal de l'Afrique Centrale, Annales, Serie in- 8 o, Sciences Zoologiques 221: 1 - 472." type="journal article" year="1977">Basilewsky (1977: 93)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="8.[192,1440,449,538]" pageId="8" pageNumber="7">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,440,449,474]" pageId="8" pageNumber="7">Taxonomic Notes.</emphasis>
This species was considered a subspecies of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Chaudoir" authorityYear="1870" box="[1000,1147,450,474]" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Graphipterus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="7" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fasciatus">
<emphasis box="[1000,1147,450,474]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="7">G. fasciatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by 
<bibRefCitation author="Burgeon, L." box="[1194,1384,450,474]" pageId="8" pageNumber="7" pagination="273 - 351" refId="ref7492" refString="Burgeon, L. 1929. Monographie du genre Graphipterus Latr. Annales de la Societe Entomologique du Belgique 69: 273 - 351." type="journal article" year="1929">Burgeon (1929)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation author="Basilewsky, P." box="[192,414,482,506]" pageId="8" pageNumber="7" pagination="1 - 472" refId="ref7374" refString="Basilewsky, P. 1977. Revision du genre Graphipterus Latreille (Coleoptera Carabidae). Musee Royal de l'Afrique Centrale, Annales, Serie in- 8 o, Sciences Zoologiques 221: 1 - 472." type="journal article" year="1977">Basilewsky (1977)</bibRefCitation>
but the lack of any intergrade specimens between these two rather distinctive forms suggests that two separate species are indicated.
</paragraph>
